<h1 class="title toc-ignore">Analytics Paper 2</h1>
<h4 class="author"><em>Donna Baret</em></h4>
<h4 class="date"><em>March 29, 2019</em></h4>

</div>


<p>After running a GLM model in predicting a movie’s review, the Final Model for Predicting the Probability of having a ‘Recommended’ Review remark is : logit(Review = Recommended) = -2.519170e-01 + 1.229775e-08 Budget + -1.786033e+00 Sequel + 1.311648e-08 Gross - -4.696765e-04 Screens</p>
<p>In this paper, we present different methods to do create the “best model” to explain (and/or best predict) the probability of a movie having a “RECOMMENDED” review.</p>
<div id="loading-libraries-and-packages" class="section level2">
<h2>Loading Libraries and Packages</h2>
</div>
<div id="a.-decision-trees" class="section level2">
<h2>A. Decision Trees</h2>
<div id="cart-or-rpart" class="section level3">
<h3>1. (CART or RPART)</h3>
<p>Find/recommend a pruned (recursive partitioning) classification tree. Experiment/investigate on different strategies for growing your tree, and on different strategies for tree-depths and/or pruning methods.</p>
<p>Using RPART, we used the variables that are fund significant in our Generalized Linear Model, Budget, Screens, and Sequel. We ran rpart using 3 methods</p>
<ol style="list-style-type: decimal">
<li>USing an unpruned tree</li>
</ol>
<p>2.Pruning the tree based on a optimal complexity parameter value.</p>
<ol start="3" style="list-style-type: decimal">
<li>Setting a complexity parameter</li>
</ol>
<p>We will compare the trees based on their relative error, xerror, and xstd. Moreover, we will also compare their prediction accuracies.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>mydata1 &lt;- read.csv(&quot;C:\\Users\\baretd\\Desktop\\STAT 218\\Analytics Project 2\\Analytics Procject 2\\Movie Gross Income and Review.csv&quot;)
str(mydata1)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## 'data.frame':    395 obs. of  11 variables:
##  $ gross    : int  9130 192000000 30700000 106000000 17300000 29000 42600000 5750000 26000000 48600000 ...
##  $ review   : Factor w/ 2 levels &quot;NOT RECOMMENDED&quot;,..: 1 2 1 1 1 1 1 2 1 1 ...
##  $ budget   : int  4000000 50000000 28000000 110000000 3500000 500000 40000000 20000000 28000000 12500000 ...
##  $ screens  : int  45 3306 2872 3470 2310 1507 3158 818 2714 2253 ...
##  $ sequel   : Factor w/ 2 levels &quot;Main&quot;,&quot;Sequel&quot;: 1 2 1 2 2 1 1 1 1 1 ...
##  $ sentiment: int  0 2 0 0 0 0 0 2 3 0 ...
##  $ views    : int  3280543 583289 304861 452917 3145573 91137 3013011 1854103 2213659 5218079 ...
##  $ likes    : int  4632 3465 328 2429 12163 112 9595 2207 2210 11709 ...
##  $ dislikes : int  425 61 34 132 610 7 419 197 419 532 ...
##  $ comments : int  636 186 47 590 1082 1 1020 593 382 770 ...
##  $ followers: int  1120000 12350000 483000 568000 1923800 310000 8153000 130655 125646 21697300 ...</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>mydata1 &lt;- mydata1[ , -1]
##################
##Rpart
##################
# cART or Rpart -----
mytree &lt;- rpart(review ~ budget + screens + sequel, data=mydata1, method=&quot;class&quot;)
rpart.plot(mytree)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<pre class="r"><code># Pruning tree  ----
printcp(mytree)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## 
## Classification tree:
## rpart(formula = review ~ budget + screens + sequel, data = mydata1, 
##     method = &quot;class&quot;)
## 
## Variables actually used in tree construction:
## [1] budget  screens sequel 
## 
## Root node error: 181/395 = 0.45823
## 
## n= 395 
##

## 1 0.176796      0   1.00000 1.00000 0.054710

## 6 0.010000      9   0.59116 0.80110 0.052927</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>#mytree$cptable
plotcp(mytree)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<pre class="r"><code>#get the optimal complexity parameter value
cp.min &lt;- mytree$cptable[which.min(mytree$cptable[,&quot;xerror&quot;]),&quot;CP&quot;]
mytree.prune &lt;- prune(mytree,cp.min)
print(mytree.prune)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## n= 395

## node), split, n, loss, yval, (yprob)

##

<div id="chaid" class="section level3">
<h3>2.(CHAID)</h3>
<p>Find/recommend a CHAID-based tree. Consider using either equal frequencies or equal widths to define 10 bins (or categories) for (each of the) continuous variables. Also, experiment/investigate on choice of the level of significance (consider 0.01, 0.05, 0.10, 0.15, 0.20, 0.30).</p>
<pre class="r"><code>mydata1$budget &lt;- as.factor( cut(mydata1$budget,10, labels=F))
#mydata1$budget &lt;- factor(round(mydata1$budget))
mydata1$screens &lt;- as.factor( cut(mydata1$screens,10, labels=F))

is.factor(mydata1$sequel)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] TRUE</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>cc1 &lt;- chaid_control(alpha2 = 0.01)
cc2 &lt;- chaid_control(alpha2 = 0.05)
cc3 &lt;- chaid_control(alpha2 = 0.10)
cc4 &lt;- chaid_control(alpha2 = 0.15)
cc5 &lt;- chaid_control(alpha2 = 0.20)
cc6 &lt;- chaid_control(alpha2 = 0.30)

DT_chaid1 &lt;- chaid(review ~ budget + screens + sequel, data = mydata1 , control = cc1)
print(DT_chaid1)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## 
## Model formula:
## review ~ budget + screens + sequel
## 
## Fitted party:
## [1] root
## |   [2] budget in 1, 2, 9
## |   |   [3] sequel in Main
## |   |   |   [4] screens in 1: RECOMMENDED (n = 65, err = 38.5%)
## |   |   |   [5] screens in 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10: NOT RECOMMENDED (n = 175, err = 33.1%)

<pre class="r"><code># Conditional Inference Tree -----

ct1 &lt;- ctree_control(teststat = &quot;quad&quot;, testtype = &quot;Bonferroni&quot;)
ct2 &lt;- ctree_control(teststat = &quot;quad&quot;, testtype =  &quot;MonteCarlo&quot;)              
ct3 &lt;- ctree_control(teststat = &quot;quad&quot;, testtype = &quot;Univariate&quot;)

ct.fit1 &lt;- ctree(review ~ budget + screens + sequel, data = mydata1, control = ct1)
ct.fit2 &lt;- ctree(review ~ budget + screens + sequel, data = mydata1, control = ct2)
ct.fit3 &lt;- ctree(review ~ budget + screens + sequel, data = mydata1, control = ct3)

plot(ct.fit1)</code></pre>

<div id="b.-non-linear-classifiers" class="section level2">
<h2>B. Non-Linear Classifiers</h2>
<ol style="list-style-type: decimal">
<li>(kNN or k nearest neighbors) Using insights from your decision trees and/or from your recommended GLM/logistic model (from Project 1), find/recommend a kNN-based classification model. Exclude SEQUEL as a predictor variable. Experiment on the choice of distance measure and the value of k (neighborhood size).</li>
</ol>
<p>sing insights from your decision trees and/or from your recommended GLM/logistic model (from Project 1), we use budget sequence and sequel to classify if a movie will have a movie is recommended by majority of the critics or not. In this classification, we exclude sequel and experiment on the choice of distance measure (Euclidean , Squared Euclidean) and the value of recommended size ( k= 3, k=10)</p>
<pre class="r"><code>mydata2 &lt;-  read.csv(&quot;C:\\Users\\baretd\\Desktop\\STAT 218\\Analytics Project 2\\Analytics Procject 2\\Movie Gross Income and Review.csv&quot;)

str(mydata2)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## 'data.frame':    395 obs. of  11 variables:
##  $ gross    : int  9130 192000000 30700000 106000000 17300000 29000 42600000 5750000 26000000 48600000 ...
##  $ review   : Factor w/ 2 levels &quot;NOT RECOMMENDED&quot;,..: 1 2 1 1 1 1 1 2 1 1 ...
##  $ budget   : int  4000000 50000000 28000000 110000000 3500000 500000 40000000 20000000 28000000 12500000 ...
##  $ screens  : int  45 3306 2872 3470 2310 1507 3158 818 2714 2253 ...
##  $ sequel   : Factor w/ 2 levels &quot;Main&quot;,&quot;Sequel&quot;: 1 2 1 2 2 1 1 1 1 1 ...
##  $ sentiment: int  0 2 0 0 0 0 0 2 3 0 ...
##  $ views    : int  3280543 583289 304861 452917 3145573 91137 3013011 1854103 2213659 5218079 ...
##  $ likes    : int  4632 3465 328 2429 12163 112 9595 2207 2210 11709 ...
##  $ dislikes : int  425 61 34 132 610 7 419 197 419 532 ...
##  $ comments : int  636 186 47 590 1082 1 1020 593 382 770 ...
##  $ followers: int  1120000 12350000 483000 568000 1923800 310000 8153000 130655 125646 21697300 ...</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>by_review &lt;- mydata2 %&gt;% group_by(review)
by_review$id &lt;- 1:nrow(mydata2)

by_review &lt;- by_review %&gt;% ungroup(review)
by_review[ ,3:4] &lt;- scale(by_review[ ,3:4])


set.seed(143)
mytrain &lt;- sample_frac(by_review, 0.7)
mytest &lt;- by_review[-mytrain$id, ]

table(mytrain$review)</code></pre>

<div id="d.compare-the-important-predictors-being-suggested-from-the-different-models-linear-model-as-yousuggested-in-project-1-decision-trees-part-a-nonlinear-classifiers-part-b-and-ensemble-learning-part-c." class="section level2">
<h2>D.Compare the important predictors being suggested from the different models: linear model (as yousuggested in Project 1), decision trees (part A), nonlinear classifiers (part B), and ensemble learning (part C).</h2>
<p>Comparing the different predictors being suggested from the different models:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type: decimal">
<li>Linear Models Suggested - Budget, Sequel, Gross, Screens</li>
<li>Decision Trees- Budget, Sequel, Screens</li>
<li>Non-Linear Classifiers- Budget, Screens</li>
<li>Ensemble Learning - Budget</li>
</ol>
<p>Linear model can take in any types of values and interpretation of results is intuitive except for the fact that interpretation is just linear. Classifying using Decision Trees such as RPART and CHAID is pretty straight forward too and requires little effort on interpretation, moreover, it does not require a linear relationships between the variables. However, CHAID requires a little more step in terms of data preparation as it does not accept continuous variables. Nevertheless, interpretation is straightforward too. Non- Linear classifiers – QDA and KNN led to good clasification results too. However, it doesn’t accept categorical independent variables which limited our variable classifiers.</p>
</div>
